List<LessonModel> l = new List();

    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "Discover how your attention works",
      stagenumber: 1,
      group: "Attention",
      title: "Spontaneous movements of attention",
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "To develop stable attention you must understand its opposite. It moves in three different ways: scanning, getting captured and alternating."
        },
        "2": {
          "text":
              "Scanning is when our focus moves from object to object, searching the outer world or the contents of our mind for something of interest. "
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "Getting captured, happens when an object, like a thought, bodily sensation, or some external stimulus, captures our attention."
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "Alternating attention, occurs when the focus moves rapidly between different objects creating the illusion that we are paying attention to two or more things simultaneously."
        },
        "5": {
          "text":
              "Don’t confuse when we are focused on something and certain things stand out from peripheral awareness. But how do you sustain attention?"
        }
      },
    ));

    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "How to develop a strong attention",
      stagenumber: 1,
      group: "Attention",
      title: "Directing and sustaining attention",
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "Directing attention means that we make a conscious decision on what to pay attention to. After directing your attention, you’ll realize that your mind has wandered off."
        },
        "2": {
          "text":
              "This happens, because you can voluntarily direct attention but sustaining works unconsciously."
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "An unconscious process weighs the importance of what we’re focusing against other possible objects of attention. But we can still influence it."
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "Just by coming back to a chosen object whenever we get distracted, we’re training that unconscious process to help us be focused more continuously. The next will be training the scope"
        },
      },
    ));

    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "Controlling how wide or narrow",
      group: "Attention",
      stagenumber: 1,
      title: "The scope of attention",
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "After directing and sustaining attention, you will work on controlling the scope of attention: how wide or narrow you want your focus to be.  Many tasks require us to expand or contract our focus. "
        },
        "2": {
          "text": "When threading a needle or hearing someone in a noisy room."
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "When watching football, our attention might expand to all the action on the field."
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "Although we do have some control, without training, our scope tends to change automatically.  Determining the scope will be cultivated in stage six."
        },
      },
    ));

    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "Controlling how wide or narrow",
      group: "Mindfulness",
      stagenumber: 1,
      title: "What is mindfulness",
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "When we lose mindfulness we become so entangled in our own thoughts and emotions that we forget the bigger picture. We do and say regretful things that cause needless suffering to ourselves and others."
        },
        "2": {
          "text":
              "Mindfulness allows us to recognize our options, choose our response wisely and take control over the direction of our lives."
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "It also gives the power to change our past conditioning and become the person we want to be."
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "To define it, mindfulness is the optimal interaction between attention and peripheral awareness, which requires increasing the conscious power of the mind. I’ll go more in depth in the next courses."
        },
      },
    ));

    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "Work on what is good for you",
      group: "Mindfulness",
      title: "Cultivating mindfulness",
      stagenumber: 1,
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "Why aren’t we naturally more mindful? First, most of us don’t use peripheral awareness effectively. Second, we don't have enough conscious power to sustain mindfulness, at the moments we need it most."
        },
        "2": {
          "text":
              "The first one is “awareness deficit disorder”. Most people overuse attention because it’s under our conscious control. "
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "Think of consciousness as a limited power source. Both attention and awareness draw their energy from it. "
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "For example, when we are in love, we lose track of what is happening around us."
        },
        "5": {
          "text":
              "The goal is to increase the total power of consciousness for both attention and awareness. But how do you train it?"
        }
      },
    ));

