    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "Learn how they work together",
      group: "Attention vs peripheral awareness",
      title: "Working together",
      stagenumber: 1,
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "Attention analyzes our experience, peripheral awareness provides the context. When one or the other doesn’t do its job we respond less effectively. "
        },
        "2": {
          "text":
              "Say you’re having a conversation while walking, while out of the corner you notice a shape moving towards you.  "
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "Awareness, alerts attention, which quickly processes the information "
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "If they were using too much attention on the conversation, peripheral awareness wouldn’t have done its job and maybe another thing would have happened..."
        },
      },
    ));

    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "How to ",
      group: "Attention vs peripheral awareness",
      title: "See things more objectively",
      stagenumber: 1,
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "Together they help us see things more objectively. Attention alone, involves a strong concern for self.  "
        },
        "2": {
          "text":
              "Considering that part of attentions’ job is to evaluate the importance of things in terms of our personal well-being.   "
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "It also means that objects of attention can be easily distorted by fear, desire or aversion. Or to identify with external objects or mental states  “I am angry, this is my car”.  "
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "Peripheral awareness is less personal and takes things more objectively as they are. "
        },
        "5": {
          "text":
              "We may be peripheral aware that some annoyance is arising, this is very different from the thought I am annoyed."
        }
      },
    ));

    l.add(new LessonModel(
      description: "Looking from both sides",
      group: "Attention vs peripheral awareness",
      title: "Introspective vs extrospective",
      stagenumber: 1,
      text: {
        "1": {
          "text":
              "Attention and peripheral awareness can be either introspective or extrospective."
        },
        "2": {
          "text":
              "Extrospective means that attention or awareness is directed towards objects outside the mind.   "
        },
        "3": {
          "text":
              "Introspective means the objects in consciousness are internal. But only peripheral awareness can observe the overall state of mind.”.  "
        },
        "4": {
          "text":
              "It’s called metacognitive introspective awareness. Attention  can’t observe activities of the mind, it can’t attend attention."
        },
        "5": {
          "text":
              "For example if you are focused on remembering you can’t focus to know you’re remembering. But you can be aware that you’re remembering."
        }
      },
    ));

    for (LessonModel lesson in l) {
      await addLesson(lesson);
    }